=\n | isbn =}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Nomani\n | first = Shibli\n | authorlink = Shibli Nomani\n | title = Sirat Al-Nabi\n | publisher = Pakistan Historical Society\n | year = 1970\n |url=\n | isbn =}}\n* {{cite book\n | last=Reeves\n | first=Minou\n | authorlink=Minou Reeves\n | title=[[Muhammad in Europe]]: A Thousand Years of Western Myth-Making\n | year=2003\n | publisher=NYU Press\n | isbn=978-0-8147-7564-6\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Rodinson\n | first = Maxime\n | authorlink = Maxime Rodinson\n | title = Muhammad\n | publisher = Allen Lane the Penguin Press\n | year = 1971\n |url=https://books.google.com/?id=LqR_mU0qpE4C&dq=muhammad+rodinson\n | isbn =978-1-86064-827-4}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Watt\n | first = William Montgomery\n | authorlink = William Montgomery Watt\n | title = Muhammad at Medina\n | publisher = Clarendon Press\n | year = 1956\n |url=https://archive.org/details/muhammadatmedina029655mbp\n | isbn = 0-19-577286-5}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Watt\n | first = William Montgomery\n | authorlink = William Montgomery Watt\n | title = Muhammad: Prophet and Statesman\n | publisher = Oxford University Press\n | year = 1974\n |url=https://books.google.com/?id=zLN2hNidLw4C&dq=muhammad+watt\n | isbn = 0-19-881078-4}}\n\n{{Wives of Muhammad}}\n{{Honoured women in Islam}}\n{{Characters and names in the Quran}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muhammads Wives}}\n[[Category:Marriage in Islam]]\n[[Category:Wives of Muhammad|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of wives]]\n<!-- section 1 -->\n[[Category:Polygyny]]\n[[Category:Ahl al-Bayt]]\n", "name_user": "2405:204:9618:7a20:963c:8e42:d3b2:c6a7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eZaynab bint Jahsh)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muhammad%27s_wives"}
{"title_page": "Hamodia", "text_new": "{{Infobox newspaper \n|name         =  Hamodia \n|image        = [[Image:Hamodia-newspaper.jpg|border]] \n|caption      = Front page of ''Hamodia'' daily \n|type         = Daily newspaper \n|format       = [[Broadsheet]] \n|foundation   = 1950 \n|publisher    = Ruth Lichtenstein\n|political    = [[Haredi Judaism]]\n|headquarters = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]] \n|editor       = \n|website      = {{url|hamodia.com}}\n|circulation  = \n|publishing_country = Israel\n}}\n'''''Hamodia''''' ({{lang-he|\u05d4\u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05e2}} \u2013 \"''the Informer''\") is a [[Hebrew language|Hebrew-language]] daily newspaper published in [[Jerusalem]]. A daily [[English language|English-language]] edition is also published in the United States, and weekly English-language editions in England and Israel. A weekly edition for [[French language|French-speaking]] readers debuted in 2008. The newspaper's slogan is \"The Newspaper of Torah Jewry\". It comes with two magazines, ''Inyan'' and ''Binyan''. ''[[Haaretz]]'', the newspaper of Israel's secular left, describes ''Hamodia'' as one of the \"most powerful\" newspapers in the [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] community.<ref name=\"Chizhik-Goldschmidt\">{{cite news|last1=Chizhik-Goldschmidt|first1=Avital|title=Inside the World of ultra-Orthodox Media: Haredi Journalists Tell It Like It Is|url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-features/.premium-1.669916|accessdate=11 August 2015|publisher=Haaretz|date=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Hamodia'' was founded in 1950 by Rabbi Yehuda Leib Levin, son of the [[Agudat Israel]] leader Rabbi [[Yitzhak-Meir Levin]] of [[Warsaw]] and [[Jerusalem]].\n\nIts current director general is Rabbi Chaim Moshe Knopf, and its deputy director general is Knopf's son, Rabbi Elazar Knopf.<ref>Marks, Yehudah. \"Mrs. Leah Knopf, ''a\"h''\". ''Hamodia'', April 19, 2012, p. A24. Retrieved April 28, 2012.</ref>\n\n==English-language edition==\nThe English-language edition of ''Hamodia'' is published by Levin's daughter, Ruth Lichtenstein. It was first printed on February 27, 1998, as a weekly paper, and on December 15, 2003, it expanded to include a daily publication as well. The daily edition is published from Monday to Friday, with no edition appearing on Saturday (the [[Jewish Sabbath]]), Sunday, or the week of [[Passover]], or the week of [[Sukkot]]. The weekly edition is printed on Wednesdays, and includes expanded sections and a glossy magazine. The English-language ''Hamodia'' is published in four editions: United States (daily and weekly), Israel (weekly only), Australia (weekly only), and Britain (weekly only). The daily edition of the American ''Hamodia'' is also available in a digital online edition. The American version is the first [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] Jewish daily newspaper ever published in English in the U.S.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n\n==Editorial policy==\nEditorial policy reflects the Haredi point of view. Although [[Zionism#Haredi Judaism and Zionism|not Zionist, on ideological grounds]], it is right of center in its Israeli coverage. It is very vociferous on the thorny issue of Jerusalem, and opposes even minimal concessions. It includes editorials on all sides of American political and economic issues. However, regarding same-sex marriage, the newspaper does not even use that name, but rather uses \"immorality\" (as in: ''The Supreme Court has announced it will rule in an immorality case''). \n\nThe publication adheres to the Orthodox interpretation of ''[[tzniut]]'' that prohibits photographs of women on its pages and website. It avoids sensationalism and reveling in tragedies.<ref name=\"Chizhik-Goldschmidt\" /> As Haredi culture shuns television, internet usage, and the reading of [[secular]] newspapers, ''Hamodia'' is one of the few news sources available to many of its readers. At first, the publishers refused to produce an internet edition of ''Hamodia'', but it now exists.\n\n==Notable journalists and writers==\n*Rabbi [[Dovid Kaplan]], ''[[Jewish education|chinuch]]'' (Jewish education) columnist<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lrB7EllYTvkC&pg=PR10|title=Polishing Diamonds: Bringing out the sparkle in our children|year=2005|isbn=965-90652-5-6|publisher=Hamodia Publishing|first=Dovid|last=Kaplan|pages=IX-X}}</ref> \n* Rabbi [[Issamar Ginzberg]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ginzberg|first1=Issamar|title=Why Strangers Are Better Than Friends|url=http://www.issamar.com/wp-content/uploads/20141001_XHM_FBY_PG0551.pdf|work=Hamodia|issue=FEATURES|date=October 1, 2014|quote=A big mistake many of us make is assuming that if we are going into business, we should look for who we know in that business.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ginzberg|first1=Issamar|title=Copywriting and TRWN The most important business formula you\u2019ve never come across|url=http://www.issamar.com/wp-content/uploads/20140923_XHM_FBY_PG058-11.pdf|work=Hamodia|date=September 23, 2014}}</ref>\n* Rebbetzin [[Tziporah Heller]], columnist<ref name=\"Heller\">{{Cite news |last=Heller |first=Tziporah |url=https://hamodia.com/2017/07/12/every-jew-precious/ |title=Every Jew Is Precious |date=July 12, 2017 |work=Hamodia |access-date= April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n* Rabbi Dr. [[Abraham J. Twerski]]<ref name=\"Twersky\">{{Cite news |last= Twersky |first=Harav Boruch Benzion |url=https://hamodia.com/2015/01/06/vanquish-yetzer-hara/ |title=To Vanquish the Yetzer Hara |date=January 6, 2015 |work=Hamodia |access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Israeli newspapers]]\n*[[Binah (magazine)|''Binah'' magazine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hamodia.com Official website]\n*[http://www.hamodia.co.uk/ Official UK website]\n\n{{Newspapers in Israel}}\n{{Organized Jewish Life in the United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1950 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in Israel]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:English-language newspapers published in Asia]]\n[[Category:French-language newspapers published in Asia]]\n[[Category:Haredi Judaism in Europe]]\n[[Category:Haredi newspapers]]\n[[Category:Hebrew-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Jewish newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Media in Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1950]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox newspaper \n|name         =  Hamodia \n|image        = [[Image:Hamodia-newspaper.jpg|border]] \n|caption      = Front page of ''Hamodia'' daily \n|type         = Daily newspaper \n|format       = [[Broadsheet]] \n|foundation   = 1950 \n|publisher    = Ruth Lichtenstein\n|political    = [[Haredi Judaism]]\n|headquarters = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]] \n|editor       = \n|website      = {{url|hamodia.com}}\n|circulation  = \n|publishing_country = Israel\n}}\n'''''Hamodia''''' ({{lang-he|\u05d4\u05de\u05d5\u05d3\u05d9\u05e2}} \u2013 \"''the Informer''\") is a [[Hebrew language|Hebrew-language]] daily newspaper published in [[Jerusalem]]. A daily [[English language|English-language]] edition is also published in the United States, and weekly English-language editions in England and Israel. A weekly edition for [[French language|French-speaking]] readers debuted in 2008. The newspaper's slogan is \"The Newspaper of Torah Jewry\". It comes with two magazines, ''Inyan'' and ''Binyan''. ''[[Haaretz]]'', the newspaper of Israel's secular left, describes ''Hamodia'' as one of the \"most powerful\" newspapers in the [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] community.<ref name=\"Chizhik-Goldschmidt\">{{cite news|last1=Chizhik-Goldschmidt|first1=Avital|title=Inside the World of ultra-Orthodox Media: Haredi Journalists Tell It Like It Is|url=http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/jewish-world-features/.premium-1.669916|accessdate=11 August 2015|publisher=Haaretz|date=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Hamodia'' was founded in 1950 by Rabbi Yehuda Leib Levin, son of the [[Agudat Israel]] leader Rabbi [[Yitzhak-Meir Levin]] of [[Warsaw]] and [[Jerusalem]].\n\nIts current director general is Rabbi Chaim Moshe Knopf, and its deputy director general is Knopf's son, Rabbi Elazar Knopf.<ref>Marks, Yehudah. \"Mrs. Leah Knopf, ''a\"h''\". ''Hamodia'', April 19, 2012, p. A24. Retrieved April 28, 2012.</ref>\n\n==English-language edition==\nThe English-language edition of ''Hamodia'' is published by Levin's daughter, Ruth Lichtenstein. It was first printed on February 27, 1998, as a weekly paper, and on December 15, 2003, it expanded to include a daily publication as well. The daily edition is published from Monday to Friday, with no edition appearing on Saturday (the [[Jewish Sabbath]]), Sunday, or the week of [[Passover]], or the week of [[Sukkot]]. The weekly edition is printed on Wednesdays, and includes expanded sections and a glossy magazine. The English-language ''Hamodia'' is published in four editions: United States (daily and weekly), Israel (weekly only), Australia (weekly only), and Britain (weekly only). The daily edition of the American ''Hamodia'' is also available in a digital online edition. The American version is the first [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] Jewish daily newspaper ever published in English in the U.S.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}}\n\n<br />\n\n==Editorial policy==\nEditorial policy reflects the Haredi point of view. Although [[Zionism#Haredi Judaism and Zionism|not Zionist, on ideological grounds]], it is right of center in its Israeli coverage. It is very vociferous on the thorny issue of Jerusalem, and opposes even minimal concessions. It includes editorials on all sides of American political and economic issues. However, regarding same-sex marriage, the newspaper does not even use that name, but rather uses \"immorality\" (as in: ''The Supreme Court has announced it will rule in an immorality case''). \n\nThe publication adheres to the Orthodox interpretation of ''[[tzniut]]'' that prohibits photographs of women on its pages and website. It avoids sensationalism and reveling in tragedies.<ref name=\"Chizhik-Goldschmidt\" /> As Haredi culture shuns television, internet usage, and the reading of [[secular]] newspapers, ''Hamodia'' is one of the few news sources available to many of its readers. At first, the publishers refused to produce an internet edition of ''Hamodia'', but it now exists.\n\n==Notable journalists and writers==\n*Rabbi [[Dovid Kaplan]], ''[[Jewish education|chinuch]]'' (Jewish education) columnist<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lrB7EllYTvkC&pg=PR10|title=Polishing Diamonds: Bringing out the sparkle in our children|year=2005|isbn=965-90652-5-6|publisher=Hamodia Publishing|first=Dovid|last=Kaplan|pages=IX-X}}</ref> \n* Rabbi [[Issamar Ginzberg]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ginzberg|first1=Issamar|title=Why Strangers Are Better Than Friends|url=http://www.issamar.com/wp-content/uploads/20141001_XHM_FBY_PG0551.pdf|work=Hamodia|issue=FEATURES|date=October 1, 2014|quote=A big mistake many of us make is assuming that if we are going into business, we should look for who we know in that business.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ginzberg|first1=Issamar|title=Copywriting and TRWN The most important business formula you\u2019ve never come across|url=http://www.issamar.com/wp-content/uploads/20140923_XHM_FBY_PG058-11.pdf|work=Hamodia|date=September 23, 2014}}</ref>\n* Rebbetzin [[Tziporah Heller]], columnist<ref name=\"Heller\">{{Cite news |last=Heller |first=Tziporah |url=https://hamodia.com/2017/07/12/every-jew-precious/ |title=Every Jew Is Precious |date=July 12, 2017 |work=Hamodia |access-date= April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n* Rabbi Dr. [[Abraham J. Twerski]]<ref name=\"Twersky\">{{Cite news |last= Twersky |first=Harav Boruch Benzion |url=https://hamodia.com/2015/01/06/vanquish-yetzer-hara/ |title=To Vanquish the Yetzer Hara |date=January 6, 2015 |work=Hamodia |access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Israeli newspapers]]\n*[[Binah (magazine)|''Binah'' magazine]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hamodia.com Official website]\n*[http://www.hamodia.co.uk/ Official UK website]\n\n{{Newspapers in Israel}}\n{{Organized Jewish Life in the United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1950 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in Israel]]\n[[Category:Daily newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:English-language newspapers published in Asia]]\n[[Category:French-language newspapers published in Asia]]\n[[Category:Haredi Judaism in Europe]]\n[[Category:Haredi newspapers]]\n[[Category:Hebrew-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Jewish newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Media in Jerusalem]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1950]]\n[[Category:Weekly newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "spacing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamodia"}
{"title_page": "Martin Hall (academic)", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Martin Hall\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image       =         File:Professor Martin Hall.jpg<!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size  = \n| alt         = Martin Hall in 2003\n| caption     = Martin Hall in 2003\n| birth_date  =         <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| birth_place = [[Guildford]],<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Salford]]|url=http://www.corporate.salford.ac.uk/leadership-management/martin-hall/biography/|title=Biography: Professor Martin Hall|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref> [[England]]\n| death_date  =         <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| residence   = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = British and South African citizenship\n| fields      = [[Archaeology]] and [[Anthropology]]\n| workplaces  =  [[University of Cape Town]], [[University of Salford]]\n| patrons     = \n| education   = [[Chichester High School For Boys]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Cambridge University]]\n| thesis_title =        <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =         <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =         <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor =    <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse      =        Brenda Cooper <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner     =         <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children    = \n| signature   =         <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =         {{URL|martinhallfacilitation.org}}\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Martin Hall''' (born in [[Guildford]],<ref name=\"biography\"/> [[England]]) is a British-South African academic and educationalist who has written extensively on [[South African history]], culture and higher education policy. He is a former Vice Chancellor of the [[University of Salford]].<ref name=biography/>\n\n==Early life==\nHall studied at [[Chichester High School For Boys]], one of the two state schools in the United Kingdom at the time that prepared students for [[Oxbridge]] admission.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/nov/25/salford-university-martin-hall-vicechancellor|title=Ready for a chilly winter|accessdate=2009-09-23 | location=London | first=Linda | last=Nordling | date=2008-11-25}}</ref> He was the first in his family to complete university.<ref name=guardian/> He completed his bachelor's degree in [[archaeology]] and [[anthropology]] at [[Cambridge University]] in 1974.<ref name=\"UCTCV\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]] |url=http://www.uct.ac.za/downloads/email/ABBREVIATED_CV_hall_final_19072007.pdf |title=CV: Professor Martin Hall |accessdate=2009-09-23 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nHe worked firstly in [[Lesotho]] in the area of archaeological excavation and then in London for the Southwark Archaeological Rescue Unit. He moved to South Africa in 1975 where he worked for five years as an [[Ethnoarchaeology|ethnoarchaeologist]] in the Natal Museum in [[Pietermaritzburg]]. He completed his doctoral studies at Cambridge in 1980<ref name=UCTCV/> and moved to [[Cape Town]] in the same year. He then became Chief Professional Officer for the Department of Archaeology at the [[South African Museum]].<ref name=UCTCV/>\n\n==University of Cape Town==\nHe joined the [[University of Cape Town]] Department of Archaeology in 1983 and was promoted from Associate Professor to Professor of Historical Archaeology,<ref name=\"dvc-cand\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]]|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/print/mondaypaper/archives/?id=2962|title=Five candidates shortlisted for DVC posts|accessdate=2009-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615174926/http://www.uct.ac.za/print/mondaypaper/archives/?id=2962|archive-date=15 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> becoming in due course the head of department. In 1983 he became Director of the Centre for African Studies<ref name=UCTCV/>\n\nHe was Director of the Multimedia Education Group from 1997\u20132001 at UCT.\n\nIn 1998, he was appointed as a Fellow of the University of Cape Town, and the following year became the inaugural Dean of the Higher Education Development Unit,<ref name=UCTCV/> charged with coordinating support for students from underprivileged backgrounds.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nIn 1999 he was appointed as President of the [[World Archaeological Congress]]<ref name=dvc-cand/> and also served as General Secretary of the South African Archaeological Society.\n\nIn 2002 he was promoted to deputy vice-chancellor<ref name=UCTCV/> and held this position for six years with responsibilities for strategic, academic and budget planning. He stepped down from this position at the end of August 2008 to take up a position at the Graduate School of Business.<ref name=\"uctpress\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]]|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/dailynews/archives/?id=6872|title=Martin Hall to take the helm at Salford|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref>\n\nHe is a fellow of the [[Royal Society of South Africa]].<ref name=dvc-cand/>\n\nHe is part of Flooved advisory board.\n\n==University of Salford==\nShort-listed for the position of Chancellor at the University of Massachusetts Ahmherst, Hall was however unsuccessful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umass.edu/newsoffice/article/hall-offers-outsiders-perspective-chancellors-job|title=Hall offers outsider's perspective to chancellor's job|website=Office of News & Media Relations &#124; UMass Amherst}}</ref> He was to be appointed a few months later, in October 2008, as the next vice-chancellor.<ref name=\"salfordvc\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Salford]]|url=http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/779|title=Salford University appoints Vice-Chancellor from South Africa|accessdate=2009-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805224156/http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/779|archive-date=5 August 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/nov/25/salford-university-martin-hall-vicechancellor</ref> He arrived at Salford in April 2009 as vice-chancellor designate and officially took up the post on 1 August 2009.<ref>http://staff.salford.ac.uk/newsitem/983</ref> Hall stated in June 2013 that Salford had had \"too aggressive an industrial-relations stance in previous years.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/salfords-vice-chancellors-candid-mea-culpa/2004767.article|title=Salford\u2019s vice-chancellor\u2019s candid mea culpa|date=13 June 2013|website=Times Higher Education (THE)}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHall holds joint British and South African citizenship.<ref name=salfordvc/> His wife, Professor Brenda Cooper, is an academic specialising in post-colonial and African literature. They have three children.<ref name=guardian/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Publications==\n*Hall, Martin 2000. \u201cArchaeology and the Modern World: Colonial Transcripts in South Africa and the Chesepeake\u201c London: Routledge {{ISBN|0-415-22966-9}}\n*Hall, Martin 2009. \u201cNothing is different but everything\u2019s changed\u201d. In The Next Twenty Five Years? Affirmative Action and Higher Education in the United States and South Africa. \n*Edited by Martin Hall, Marvin Krislov and David L. Featherman. University of Michigan Press. \n*Hall, Martin 2009. \u201cNew knowledge and the university\u201d. Anthropology Southern Africa, 32 (1 and 2): 69-86.\n\n==External links==\n* {{SAHRA people | martin-hall | Martin Hall }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box|title=Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Salford]]|years=2009&ndash;2015|before=[[Michael Harloe]]|after=[[Helen Marshall (academic)|Helen Marshall]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Martin}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Salford]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African archaeologists]]\n[[Category:South African educational theorists]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town academics]]\n[[Category:Vice-Chancellors of the University of Salford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People from Guildford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name        = Martin Hall\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image       =         File:Professor Martin Hall.jpg<!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size  = \n| alt         = Martin Hall in 2003\n| caption     = Martin Hall in 2003\n| birth_date  =         <!--{{birth date |YYYY|MM|DD}}-->\n| birth_place = [[Guildford]],<ref name=\"biography\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Salford]]|url=http://www.corporate.salford.ac.uk/leadership-management/martin-hall/biography/|title=Biography: Professor Martin Hall|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref> [[England]]\n| death_date  =         <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates =  <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| other_names = \n| residence   = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = British and South African citizenship\n| fields      = [[Archaeology]] and [[Anthropology]]\n| workplaces  =  [[University of Cape Town]], [[University of Salford]]\n| patrons     = \n| education   = [[Chichester High School For Boys]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Cambridge University]]\n| thesis_title =        <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url  =         <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year =         <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor =    <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for   = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  = \n| awards      = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse      =        Brenda Cooper <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner     =         <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children    = \n| signature   =         <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt = \n| website     =         {{URL|martinhallfacilitation.org}}\n| footnotes   = \n}}\n'''Martin Hall''' (born in [[Guildford]],<ref name=\"biography\"/> [[England]]) is a British-South African academic and educationalist who has written extensively on [[South African history]], culture and higher education policy. He is a former Vice Chancellor of the [[University of Salford]].<ref name=biography/>\n\n==Early life==\nHall studied at [[Chichester High School For Boys]], one of the two state schools in the United Kingdom at the time that prepared students for [[Oxbridge]] admission.<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/nov/25/salford-university-martin-hall-vicechancellor|title=Ready for a chilly winter|accessdate=2009-09-23 | location=London | first=Linda | last=Nordling | date=2008-11-25}}</ref> He was the first in his family to complete university.<ref name=guardian/> He completed his bachelor's degree in [[archaeology]] and [[anthropology]] at [[Cambridge University]] in 1974.<ref name=\"UCTCV\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]] |url=http://www.uct.ac.za/downloads/email/ABBREVIATED_CV_hall_final_19072007.pdf |title=CV: Professor Martin Hall |accessdate=2009-09-23 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nHe worked firstly in [[Lesotho]] in the area of archaeological excavation and then in London for the Southwark Archaeological Rescue Unit. He moved to South Africa in 1975 where he worked for five years as an [[Ethnoarchaeology|ethnoarchaeologist]] in the Natal Museum in [[Pietermaritzburg]]. He completed his doctoral studies at Cambridge in 1980<ref name=UCTCV/> and moved to [[Cape Town]] in the same year. He then became Chief Professional Officer for the Department of Archaeology at the [[South African Museum]].<ref name=UCTCV/>\n\n==University of Cape Town==\nHe joined the [[University of Cape Town]] Department of Archaeology in 1983 and was promoted from Associate Professor to Professor of Historical Archaeology,<ref name=\"dvc-cand\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]]|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/print/mondaypaper/archives/?id=2962|title=Five candidates shortlisted for DVC posts|accessdate=2009-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615174926/http://www.uct.ac.za/print/mondaypaper/archives/?id=2962|archive-date=15 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> becoming in due course the head of department. In 1983 he became Director of the Centre for African Studies<ref name=UCTCV/>\n\nHe was Director of the Multimedia Education Group from 1997\u20132001 at UCT.\n\nIn 1998, he was appointed as a Fellow of the University of Cape Town, and the following year became the inaugural Dean of the Higher Education Development Unit,<ref name=UCTCV/> charged with coordinating support for students from underprivileged backgrounds.<ref name=guardian/>\n\nIn 1999 he was appointed as President of the [[World Archaeological Congress]]<ref name=dvc-cand/> and also served as General Secretary of the South African Archaeological Society.\n\nIn 2002 he was promoted to deputy vice-chancellor<ref name=UCTCV/> and held this position for six years with responsibilities for strategic, academic and budget planning. He stepped down from this position at the end of August 2008 to take up a position at the Graduate School of Business.<ref name=\"uctpress\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Cape Town]]|url=http://www.uct.ac.za/dailynews/archives/?id=6872|title=Martin Hall to take the helm at Salford|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref>\n\nHe is a fellow of the [[Royal Society of South Africa]].<ref name=dvc-cand/>\n\nHe is part of Flooved advisory board.\n\n==University of Salford==\nShort-listed for the position of Chancellor at the University of Massachusetts Ahmherst, Hall was however unsuccessful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umass.edu/newsoffice/article/hall-offers-outsiders-perspective-chancellors-job|title=Hall offers outsider's perspective to chancellor's job|website=Office of News & Media Relations &#124; UMass Amherst}}</ref> He was to be appointed a few months later, in October 2008, as the next vice-chancellor.<ref name=\"salfordvc\">{{cite web|publisher=[[University of Salford]]|url=http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/779|title=Salford University appoints Vice-Chancellor from South Africa|accessdate=2009-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805224156/http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/779|archive-date=5 August 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/education/2008/nov/25/salford-university-martin-hall-vicechancellor \"Ready for a chilly winter\"</ref> He arrived at Salford in April 2009 as vice-chancellor designate and officially took up the post on 1 August 2009.<ref>http://staff.salford.ac.uk/newsitem/983 \"New VC Designate arrives at University of Salford\"</ref> Hall stated in June 2013 that Salford had had \"too aggressive an industrial-relations stance in previous years.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/salfords-vice-chancellors-candid-mea-culpa/2004767.article|title=Salford\u2019s vice-chancellor\u2019s candid mea culpa|date=13 June 2013|website=Times Higher Education (THE)}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHall holds joint British and South African citizenship.<ref name=salfordvc/> His wife, Professor Brenda Cooper, is an academic specialising in post-colonial and African literature. They have three children.<ref name=guardian/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Publications==\n*Hall, Martin 2000. \u201cArchaeology and the Modern World: Colonial Transcripts in South Africa and the Chesepeake\u201c London: Routledge {{ISBN|0-415-22966-9}}\n*Hall, Martin 2009. \u201cNothing is different but everything\u2019s changed\u201d. In The Next Twenty Five Years? Affirmative Action and Higher Education in the United States and South Africa. \n*Edited by Martin Hall, Marvin Krislov and David L. Featherman. University of Michigan Press. \n*Hall, Martin 2009. \u201cNew knowledge and the university\u201d. Anthropology Southern Africa, 32 (1 and 2): 69-86.\n\n==External links==\n* {{SAHRA people | martin-hall | Martin Hall }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{Succession box|title=Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Salford]]|years=2009&ndash;2015|before=[[Michael Harloe]]|after=[[Helen Marshall (academic)|Helen Marshall]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hall, Martin}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Salford]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African archaeologists]]\n[[Category:South African educational theorists]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town academics]]\n[[Category:Vice-Chancellors of the University of Salford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People from Guildford]]\n", "