{"title_page": "Ulrich Kienzle", "text_new": "{{short description|German journalist}}\n[[File:Ulrich Kienzle.jpg|thumb|Ulrich Kienzle in 2017]]\n'''Ulrich Kienzle''' (9 May 1936 \u2013 16 April 2020) was a German [[journalism|journalist]] and [[publishing|publisher]]. He was renowned in Germany as an expert on politics and culture of the [[Near East|Near]] and [[Middle East]].\n\n== Life ==\nUlrich Kienzle was born in Neckargr\u00f6ningen, [[Free People's State of W\u00fcrttemberg]], today part of [[Remseck]], [[Ludwigsburg (district)|Ludwigsburg District]], [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], Germany.<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /><ref name=\"Tagesschau\" /><ref name=\"Welt\" /> He grew up in late-[[World War II]] and [[Allied-occupied Germany|post-war]] [[Swabia]] and the early [[Federal Republic of Germany]]. He earned a [[university degree]] in [[political science]] (with minors [[German studies]] and [[history of art]]), studying at [[University of Munich]] and [[University of T\u00fcbingen]] with {{ill|Theodor Eschenburg|de}} from 1956 to 1963.<ref name=\"Munzinger\" />\n\nFrom 1956 to 1967, he worked, first as a [[freelancer]], then fro 1963 as a permanent [[contributing editor]] of {{lang|de|Abendschau}} (i.e. evening news) for the TV program of the [[Stuttgart]]-based regional broadcaster [[S\u00fcddeutscher Rundfunk]] (SDR).<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /><ref name=\"Welt\" /> After a stint working for [[Westdeutscher Rundfunk]] (WDR)<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /> in 1967 and 1968, he returned to SDR, becoming lead anchor of {{lang|de|Abendschau}} from 1968. From 1972 to 1974, he was co-host/co-editor of {{lang|de|Kompass}}, a joint [[foreign affairs]] broadcast of SDR and [[Bayerischer Rundfunk]] (BR).<ref name=\"Munzinger\" />\n\nIn 1974, Kienzle started working for the national public broadcaster [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]] as [[correspondent]], from 1974 to 1977 for the [[Near East]] (stationed in [[Beirut]]). From 1977 to 1980, he was ARD's correspondent for [[Southern Africa]].<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /> From 1980 to 1990, he was [[chief editor]] of North German regional station [[Radio Bremen]].<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" />\n\nFrom 1990 to 1993, Kienzle was chief editor for foreign affairs at [[Hessischer Rundfunk]] and anchor for [[ZDF|Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen (ZDF)]], presenting foreign affairs magazine {{lang|de|Auslandsjournal}}.<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /><ref name=\"Welt\" /> In this function, he was in 1990 one of the few Western journalists allowed to interview then [[Iraq]]i dictator [[Saddam Hussein]].<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /> From 1993 to 2000, he was one of the \"combattants\" in the weekly ZDF political magazine ''Frontal'', that always featured a controversial debate between the more [[left-wing politics|leftist]] Kienzle (usually taking the position of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]]) and the more [[right-wing politics|rightist]] [[Bodo Hugo Hauser]] (usually taking the position of the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany]]).<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /><ref name=\"Tagesschau\" /><ref name=\"Welt\" />\n\nIn the 2000s, Kienzle hosted a ZDF program on the German political party's campaigns in the run up to the [[2002 German federal election|2002 federal election]], and was contributing to a ZDF magazine on the economy ({{lang|de|WISO}}) since 2003.\n\nHe was occasionally interviewed on matters of the Near and Middle East, e.g. the [[Iraq War]], the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]] and the [[Arab Spring]].\n\nKienzle died in Wiesbaden on 16 April 2020.<ref name=\"Welt\" />\n\n== Honours ==\n* 1977: [[Bundesverdienstkreuz]] (15 November 1976), for reports from the [[Lebanese civil war]]<ref>Bundespr\u00e4sidialamt</ref>\n* 1983 [[Eduard Rhein Foundation|Eduard Rhein Prize]], award for \"outstanding achievements in research and/or development in the areas of radio, television an information technology\", Culture Prize for the report ''Blutiger Sommer \u2013 Wiedersehen mit Beirut''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070612065231/http://www.eduard-rhein-stiftung.de/html/Preistraeger.html <!--|url=http://www.eduard-rhein-stiftung.de/html/Preistraeger.html |wayback=20070612065231--> Preistr\u00e4ger] (in German) Eduard Rhein Foundation, retrieved 11 August 2015</ref>\n* 1995 [[Bambi (prize)|BAMBI]], German media prize \"to recognise excellence in international media and television with vision and creativity who affected and inspired the German public\"\n* 2004 {{lang|de|Journalistenpreis des Deutschen Mittelstandes}} (\"journalist prize of the German {{lang|de|[[Mittelstand]]}}\"), for critical journalism on [[bargaining|bargain]] hunters\n\n== Publications ==\nKienzle's publications are hed by the [[German National Library]], including:<ref>[https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&reset=true&cqlMode=true&query=auRef%3D115422404&selectedCategory=any Publications by Ulrich Kienzle] [[German National Library]]</ref><ref>[https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&reset=true&cqlMode=true&query=betRef%3D115422404&selectedCategory=any Participations by Ulrich Kienzle] [[German National Library]]</ref>\n* {{lang|de|S\u00fcdafrika. Wei\u00dfe in der Wagenburg}}. Droemer Knaur, M\u00fcnchen 1985, {{ISBN|3-426-04002-6}}. (i.e. \"South Africa. Whites in the [[wagon fort]]\").\n* {{lang|de|Noch Fragen, Kienzle? Ja, Hauser! Der offizielle deutsche Meinungsf\u00fchrer}}. Hofmann & Campe, Hamburg 1995, {{ISBN|3-455-11075-4}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (i.e. \"Any more questions, Kienzle? Yes, Hauser! The official German opinion leader\").\n* {{lang|de|SchwarzRotGeld. Der offizielle deutsche Marktf\u00fchrer}}. Hoffmann & Campe, Hamburg 1997, {{ISBN|3-455-11076-2}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (i.e. \"[[Flag of Germany|Black-Red-Gold]]\". The official German guidebook on the market\")\n* {{lang|de|Total Frontal. Spr\u00fcche und Widerspr\u00fcche aus 7 TV-Jahren}}. Heyne, M\u00fcnchen 1999, {{ISBN|3-453-15530-0}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (i.e. \"Total Frontal. Quotations and controversies from seven years on TV\").\n* {{lang|de|Bitte recht feindlich! Sch\u00f6ner leben und streiten im neuen Jahrtausend}}. Heyne, M\u00fcnchen 2000, {{ISBN|3-453-16497-0}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (\"i.e. Please be quite hostile! Better living and debating in the new [[millennium]]\").\n* {{lang|de|K\u00fcchenkabinett. Essen und Trinken bei Rechten und Linken}}. Heyne, M\u00fcnchen 2001, {{ISBN|3-453-18843-8}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (i.e. \"[[Kitchen Cabinet]]. Food and Drink at rightists and leftists.)\n* {{lang|de|Wo kommsch denn Du alds Arschloch her? Die Erfindung des Schwaben; wie er wurde, was er ist; ein Essay}}. Edition Sagas, Stuttgart 2008, {{ISBN|978-3-9812510-9-8}} (mit Audio-CD). (an essay on the cultural history of the [[Swabia]]n people).\n* {{lang|de|Abschied von 1001 Nacht. Mein Versuch, die Araber zu verstehen}}. Edition Sagas, Stuttgart 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-9812510-7-4}}. (i.e. \"A farewell to [[One Thousand and One Nights]]. My attempt to understand the [[Arabs]]\").\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Hanfeld\">{{cite news\n| last = Hanfeld\n| first = Michael\n| url = https://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/medien/zum-tod-des-fernsehjournalisten-ulrich-kienzle-16729316.html\n| title = Zum Tod von Ulrich Kienzle : Auslandskorrespondent blieb er sein Leben lang\n| newspaper = [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|FAZ]]\n| date = 17 April 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 17 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Munzinger\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.munzinger.de/search/portrait/Ulrich+Kienzle/0/20723.html\n| title =  Ulrich Kienzle / deutscher Journalist und TV-Moderator \n| website = Munzinger\n| date = 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 18 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tagesschau\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/ulrich-kienzle-101.html\n| title = Ex-\"Frontal\"-Moderator Ulrich Kienzle ist tot\n| website = [[Tagesschau (German TV series)|Tagesschau]]\n| date = 17 April 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 18 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Welt\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.welt.de/kultur/medien/article207319183/Ulrich-Kienzle-Bekannter-ZDF-Moderator-ist-tot.html\n| title = Bekannter ZDF-Moderator / TV-Journalist Ulrich Kienzle ist tot]\n| newspaper = [[Die Welt]]\n| date = 17 April 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 17 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat}}\n* {{official|http://www.ulrichkienzle.de/vita.html}}\n* {{DNB portal|115422404}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kienzle, Ulrich}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:German journalists]]\n[[Category:German television journalists]]\n[[Category:German male journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German journalists]]\n[[Category:University of T\u00fcbingen alumni]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:ZDF people]]\n[[Category:ARD people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German journalist}}\n[[File:Ulrich Kienzle.jpg|thumb|Ulrich Kienzle in 2017]]\n'''Ulrich Kienzle''' (9 May 1936 \u2013 16 April 2020) was a German [[journalism|journalist]] and [[publishing|publisher]]. He was renowned in Germany as an expert on politics and culture of the [[Near East|Near]] and [[Middle East]].\n\n== Life ==\nUlrich Kienzle was born in Neckargr\u00f6ningen, [[Free People's State of W\u00fcrttemberg]], today part of [[Remseck]], [[Ludwigsburg (district)|Ludwigsburg District]], [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], Germany.<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /><ref name=\"Tagesschau\" /><ref name=\"Welt\" /> He grew up in late-[[World War II]] and [[Allied-occupied Germany|post-war]] [[Swabia]] and the early [[Federal Republic of Germany]]. He earned a [[university degree]] in [[political science]] (with minors [[German studies]] and [[history of art]]), studying at [[University of Munich]] and [[University of T\u00fcbingen]] with {{ill|Theodor Eschenburg|de}} from 1956 to 1963.<ref name=\"Munzinger\" />\n\nFrom 1956 to 1967, he worked, first as a [[freelancer]], then fro 1963 as a permanent [[contributing editor]] of {{lang|de|Abendschau}} (i.e. evening news) for the TV program of the [[Stuttgart]]-based regional broadcaster [[S\u00fcddeutscher Rundfunk]] (SDR).<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /><ref name=\"Welt\" /> After a stint working for [[Westdeutscher Rundfunk]] (WDR)<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /> in 1967 and 1968, he returned to SDR, becoming lead anchor of {{lang|de|Abendschau}} from 1968. From 1972 to 1974, he was co-host/co-editor of {{lang|de|Kompass}}, a joint [[foreign affairs]] broadcast of SDR and [[Bayerischer Rundfunk]] (BR).<ref name=\"Munzinger\" />\n\nIn 1974, Kienzle started working for the national public broadcaster [[ARD (broadcaster)|ARD]] as [[correspondent]], from 1974 to 1977 for the [[Near East]] (stationed in [[Beirut]]). From 1977 to 1980, he was ARD's correspondent for [[Southern Africa]].<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /> From 1980 to 1990, he was [[chief editor]] of North German regional station [[Radio Bremen]].<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" />\n\nFrom 1990 to 1993, Kienzle was chief editor for foreign affairs at [[Hessischer Rundfunk]] and anchor for [[ZDF|Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen (ZDF)]], presenting foreign affairs magazine {{lang|de|Auslandsjournal}}.<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /><ref name=\"Welt\" /> In this function, he was in 1990 one of the few Western journalists allowed to interview then [[Iraq]]i dictator [[Saddam Hussein]].<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /> From 1993 to 2000, he was one of the \"combattants\" in the weekly ZDF political magazine ''Frontal'', that always featured a controversial debate between the more [[left-wing politics|leftist]] Kienzle (usually taking the position of the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]]) and the more [[right-wing politics|rightist]] [[Bodo Hugo Hauser]] (usually taking the position of the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany]]).<ref name=\"Hanfeld\" /><ref name=\"Tagesschau\" /><ref name=\"Welt\" />\n\nIn the 2000s, Kienzle hosted a ZDF program on the German political party's campaigns in the run up to the [[2002 German federal election|2002 federal election]], and was contributing to a ZDF magazine on the economy ({{lang|de|WISO}}) since 2003.\n\nHe was occasionally interviewed on matters of the Near and Middle East, e.g. the [[Iraq War]], the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]] and the [[Arab Spring]].\n\nKienzle died in Wiesbaden on 16 April 2020.<ref name=\"Welt\" />\n\n== Honours ==\n* 1977: [[Bundesverdienstkreuz]] (15 November 1976), for reports from the [[Lebanese civil war]]<ref>Bundespr\u00e4sidialamt</ref>\n* 1983 [[Eduard Rhein Foundation|Eduard Rhein Prize]], award for \"outstanding achievements in research and/or development in the areas of radio, television an information technology\", Culture Prize for the report ''Blutiger Sommer \u2013 Wiedersehen mit Beirut''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070612065231/http://www.eduard-rhein-stiftung.de/html/Preistraeger.html <!--|url=http://www.eduard-rhein-stiftung.de/html/Preistraeger.html |wayback=20070612065231--> Preistr\u00e4ger] (in German) Eduard Rhein Foundation, retrieved 11 August 2015</ref>\n* 1995 [[Bambi (prize)|BAMBI]], German media prize \"to recognise excellence in international media and television with vision and creativity who affected and inspired the German public\"\n* 2004 {{lang|de|Journalistenpreis des Deutschen Mittelstandes}} (\"journalist prize of the German {{lang|de|[[Mittelstand]]}}\"), for critical journalism on [[bargaining|bargain]] hunters\n\n== Publications ==\nKienzle's publications are hed by the [[German National Library]], including:<ref>[https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&reset=true&cqlMode=true&query=auRef%3D115422404&selectedCategory=anyPublications by Ulrich Kienzle] [[German National Library]]</ref><ref>[https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&reset=true&cqlMode=true&query=betRef%3D115422404&selectedCategory=any Participations by Ulrich Kienzle] [[German National Library]]</ref>\n* {{lang|de|S\u00fcdafrika. Wei\u00dfe in der Wagenburg}}. Droemer Knaur, M\u00fcnchen 1985, {{ISBN|3-426-04002-6}}. (i.e. \"South Africa. Whites in the [[wagon fort]]\").\n* {{lang|de|Noch Fragen, Kienzle? Ja, Hauser! Der offizielle deutsche Meinungsf\u00fchrer}}. Hofmann & Campe, Hamburg 1995, {{ISBN|3-455-11075-4}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (i.e. \"Any more questions, Kienzle? Yes, Hauser! The official German opinion leader\").\n* {{lang|de|SchwarzRotGeld. Der offizielle deutsche Marktf\u00fchrer}}. Hoffmann & Campe, Hamburg 1997, {{ISBN|3-455-11076-2}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (i.e. \"[[Flag of Germany|Black-Red-Gold]]\". The official German guidebook on the market\")\n* {{lang|de|Total Frontal. Spr\u00fcche und Widerspr\u00fcche aus 7 TV-Jahren}}. Heyne, M\u00fcnchen 1999, {{ISBN|3-453-15530-0}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (i.e. \"Total Frontal. Quotations and controversies from seven years on TV\").\n* {{lang|de|Bitte recht feindlich! Sch\u00f6ner leben und streiten im neuen Jahrtausend}}. Heyne, M\u00fcnchen 2000, {{ISBN|3-453-16497-0}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (\"i.e. Please be quite hostile! Better living and debating in the new [[millennium]]\").\n* {{lang|de|K\u00fcchenkabinett. Essen und Trinken bei Rechten und Linken}}. Heyne, M\u00fcnchen 2001, {{ISBN|3-453-18843-8}} (together with Bodo H. Hauser). (i.e. \"[[Kitchen Cabinet]]. Food and Drink at rightists and leftists.)\n* {{lang|de|Wo kommsch denn Du alds Arschloch her? Die Erfindung des Schwaben; wie er wurde, was er ist; ein Essay}}. Edition Sagas, Stuttgart 2008, {{ISBN|978-3-9812510-9-8}} (mit Audio-CD). (an essay on the cultural history of the [[Swabia]]n people).\n* {{lang|de|Abschied von 1001 Nacht. Mein Versuch, die Araber zu verstehen}}. Edition Sagas, Stuttgart 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-9812510-7-4}}. (i.e. \"A farewell to [[One Thousand and One Nights]]. My attempt to understand the [[Arabs]]\").\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Hanfeld\">{{cite news\n| last = Hanfeld\n| first = Michael\n| url = https://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/medien/zum-tod-des-fernsehjournalisten-ulrich-kienzle-16729316.html\n| title = Zum Tod von Ulrich Kienzle : Auslandskorrespondent blieb er sein Leben lang\n| newspaper = [[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung|FAZ]]\n| date = 17 April 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 17 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Munzinger\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.munzinger.de/search/portrait/Ulrich+Kienzle/0/20723.html\n| title =  Ulrich Kienzle / deutscher Journalist und TV-Moderator \n| website = Munzinger\n| date = 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 18 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tagesschau\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/ulrich-kienzle-101.html\n| title = Ex-\"Frontal\"-Moderator Ulrich Kienzle ist tot\n| website = [[Tagesschau (German TV series)|Tagesschau]]\n| date = 17 April 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 18 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Welt\">{{cite news\n| url = https://www.welt.de/kultur/medien/article207319183/Ulrich-Kienzle-Bekannter-ZDF-Moderator-ist-tot.html\n| title = Bekannter ZDF-Moderator / TV-Journalist Ulrich Kienzle ist tot]\n| newspaper = [[Die Welt]]\n| date = 17 April 2020\n| language = de\n| accessdate = 17 April 2020\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat}}\n* {{official|http://www.ulrichkienzle.de/vita.html}}\n* {{DNB portal|115422404}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kienzle, Ulrich}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:German journalists]]\n[[Category:German television journalists]]\n[[Category:German male journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century German journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German journalists]]\n[[Category:University of T\u00fcbingen alumni]]\n[[Category:German male writers]]\n[[Category:ZDF people]]\n[[Category:ARD people]]\n", "name_user": "Gerda Arendt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulrich_Kienzle"}
{"title_page": "British Rail Class 91", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2012}}\n{{original research|date=June 2011}}\n{{cleanup|date=March 2012}}\n}}\n{{Infobox locomotive\n|name = British Rail Class 91 ''Electra''\n|powertype = Electric\n|image = [[File:Kings Cross - LNER 91125 ecs.JPG|300px]]\n|caption = [[London North Eastern Railway]] 91125 at {{stnlnk|London King's Cross}} in July 2018\n|builder = [[British Rail Engineering Limited|BREL]] [[Crewe Works]]\n|builddate = 1988\u20131991\n|totalproduction = 31\n|gauge = {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on|al=on}}\n|tractionmotors = GEC G426 ({{convert|1.175|MW|abbr=on|disp=or}} peak/{{convert|1.135|MW|abbr=on|disp=or}} continuous)\n|electricsystem = [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25 kV AC]] [[Overhead line|Catenary]]\n|collectionmethod = [[Brecknell Willis]] [[Pantograph (rail)|pantograph]]\n|whytetype = \n|aarwheels=B-B|uicclass = Bo'Bo'\n|tractiveeffort = ''max'' {{convert|190|kN|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"jma\"/><br>''continuous'' {{convert|107|kN|abbr=on}} @ {{convert|153|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"jma\"/>\n|trainbrakes = [[Railway air brake|Air]] ([[axle]]-mounted triple-[[Disc brake#On other vehicles|disc brakes]]; {{convert|140|\u2013|0|mph|abbr=on|disp=or}})\n|locobrakes = Primary, [[Rheostatic brake|rheostatic]] ({{convert|140|\u2013|30|mph|abbr=on|disp=or}}); secondary [[friction]] ([[Railway air brake|pneumatic]] single-[[cardan shaft]]-mounted [[Disc brake#On other vehicles|disc]] and [[Railway tread brake|tread brakes]]; {{convert|30|\u2013|0|mph|abbr=on|disp=or}})\n|locobrakeforce =''[[Dynamic braking]]:''<br>{{convert|83|kN|lbf|abbr=on|lk=in}} ''max'' @{{convert|100|to|200|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"jma\">{{citation| url =http://documents.epfl.ch/users/a/al/allenbac/www/documents/Fich0291.pdf| title = BoBo BR 91 (Spec Sheet) |language = French| work = documents.epfl.ch| author = Jean-Marc Allenbach}}</ref><br>{{convert|50|kN|lbf|abbr=on}} ''max'' @{{convert|200|to|240|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"jma\"/>\n|length  = {{convert|19.400|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"jma\"/>\n|width   =\n|height  =\n|locoweight = {{convert|81.5|t|lk=on}}\n|coupling=Hook with drophead buckeye at both ends.|maxspeed = ''Design:'' {{convert|225|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}<br />''Service:'' {{convert|125|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}<br />''Blunt-end first:'' {{convert|110|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}<br />''Lok (Overspeed):'' {{convert|240|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"jma\"/>\n|poweroutput = {{convert|4830|kW|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"jma\"/>\n|axleloadclass = [[Route availability]] 7\n|operator = [[London North Eastern Railway]]<br>[[Europhoenix]]<ref>https://www.railmagazine.com/news/network/europhoenix-earmarks-91s-for-european-freight-use</ref>\n|fleetnumbers = 91001\u201391031<br>later 91101\u201391122, 91124\u201391132\n|officialname     = \n|nicknames = Electras\n|locale           = \n|deliverydate     = \n|firstrundate     = \n|lastrundate      = \n|retiredate       = \n|withdrawndate    = \n|restoredate      = \n|scrapdate        = \n|currentowner     = [[Eversholt Rail Group]]\n|disposition      = \n}}\n\nThe [[British Rail]] '''Class 91''' is a class of [[high-speed rail|high-speed]], {{convert|4830|kW|abbr=on}} [[electric locomotive]]s ordered as a component of the [[East Coast Main Line]] modernisation and electrification programme of the late 1980s. The Class&nbsp;91s were given the auxiliary name of [[InterCity 225]] to indicate their envisaged top speed of {{convert|140|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on|order=flip}}; they were also referred to as '''Electras''' by British Rail during their development and throughout the electrification of the East Coast Main Line. The other end of the InterCity 225 train set is formed of a Mark 4 [[Driving Van Trailer]], built with a similar body shell to the Class 91 locomotives. The locomotive body shells are of all-steel construction. Unusually, the motors are body mounted and drive bogie-mounted gearboxes via [[cardan shaft]]s. This reduces the [[unsprung mass]] and hence track wear at high speeds. The locomotive also features an underslung transformer, so that the body is relatively empty compared to contemporary electric locomotives. Much of the engineering specification for the locomotive was derived from the research and operational experience of the [[Advanced Passenger Train|APT-P]].<ref name=\"jma\"/><ref>\"The Design and Development of the Class 91 Locomotive\", P J Donnison and G R West, Main Line Railway Electrification Conference 1989 - Proceedings of the Institute of Electrical Engineers, 1989.</ref><ref>\"The design, manufacture and assembly of the British Rail Class 91, 25 kV 225km/h locomotive\", M L Broom and G W Smart, Proceedings of the Institute of Mechanical Engineers Vol. 205, 1990.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1985, [[ASEA]], [[Brush Traction|Brush]] and [[General Electric Company|GEC Transportation Projects]]  tendered for the design and construction of the Class 91s.<ref>{{cite news |title= Managing Electra |authorlink=Roger Ford |author=Ford, Roger |work=[[Modern Railways]] |date=April 1988 |issn=0026-8356}}</ref> GEC subsequently won the bid and the fleet was built by sub-contractors [[British Rail Engineering Limited]]'s [[Crewe Works]] between 1988 and 1991.\n\nThe Class 91s began passenger service on 3 March 1989, when 91001 worked 1P26 17.36 London Kings Cross to Peterborough train. This train was formed of [[InterCity 125]] Mark 3 coaches and a [[British Rail Class 43 (HST)|Class 43]] power car, which had been converted for use as a [[Driving Van Trailer|DVT]] as the Mark 4 coaches were not then ready. The Class 91s then began service on King's Cross to Leeds trains on 11 March 1989, when 91008 with a rake of Intercity 125 Mark 3 coaches and power car 43068 worked the 1D32 06:50 Kings Cross to Leeds service. The set then worked 1A12, the 10:00 Leeds to London Kings Cross service.\n\nIn the early 1990s, after the cancellation of [[InterCity 250]], British Rail examined the option of ordering a further set of ten Class 91s to operate on the [[West Coast Main Line]] with UK Treasury support, however the business case for these failed to prove sufficiently worthwhile <ref>\n{{cite book\n  | last = Vincent\n  | first = Mike\n  | title = InterCity Story 1964-2012\n  | publisher = Oxford Publishing Company\n  | year = 2013\n  | isbn = 978-0860936527\n}}</ref> and led to the electric [[Networker (train)|Networker]] Classes [[British Rail Class 365|365]], [[British Rail Class 465|465]] and [[British Rail Class 466|466]] EMU Networker stock's procurement being taken forward.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n[[File:91115 at Kings Cross 4.jpg|thumb|91115 running blunt-end first at [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]]]]\n\nThe asymmetric body style is streamlined at one end to allow high-speed operation, with the fixed sets of Mark 4 coaches in normal push-pull passenger operation. An additional requirement of the design was that they could operate as normal locomotives. This led to a second cab being incorporated into the unstreamlined 'blunt end'. Operating with the blunt end first limits the maximum speed of the locomotive to {{convert|110|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, due to the aerodynamics of the pantograph's knuckle creating excessive uplift force on the OLE.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} \n\nIn July 2019, 91108 was the first of the class to be withdrawn.<ref>First Class 91 withdrawn from traffic by LNER ''[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]'' issue 884 31 July 2019 page 28</ref>\n\n===Speed record===\nA Class 91, 91010 (now 91110), holds the British locomotive speed record at {{convert|161.7|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}, set on 17 September 1989,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Class 91 hits 162 mph|page=5|issue=106|date=5\u201318 October 1989|magazine=[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]|publisher=EMAP National Publications|issn=0953-4563|oclc=49953699}}</ref> just south of Little Bytham on a test run down Stoke Bank with the DVT leading. Although [[British Rail Class 370|Class 370s]], [[British Rail Class 373|Class 373s]] and [[British Rail Class 374|Class 374s]] have run faster, all are EMUs which means that the ''Electra'' is officially the fastest locomotive in Britain. Another loco (91031, now 91131), hauling five Mk4s and a DVT on a test run, ran between [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] and {{stnlnk|Edinburgh Waverley}} in 3&nbsp;hours, 29&nbsp;minutes and 30 seconds on 26 September 1991. This is still the current record. The set covered the route in an average speed of {{convert|112.5|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} and reached the full {{convert|140|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}} several times during the run.\n\n== Fleet ==\n{{main|List of British Rail Class 91 locomotives}}\n[[File:91118 'Bradford Film Festival' at Peterborough.JPG|thumb|Class 91/1, no. 91118 [[National Media Museum|\"Bradford Film Festival\"]] at [[Peterborough]] on 27 July 2003. This locomotive is painted in [[Great North Eastern Railway|GNER]] blue livery]]\n[[File:Class91bluntendcab.jpg|thumb|The blunt end cab of a Class 91]]\n[[File:Class91cab.jpg|thumb|The normal cab of a Class 91]]\nWhen British Rail was privatised, the InterCity livery was progressively removed and new operator [[Great North Eastern Railway|GNER]] applied their corporate livery of blue and red. When GNER lost their franchise in 2007, the red stripe was replaced by a white stripe containing the words National Express and East Coast. National Express East Coast originally planned to repaint all of their InterCity 225 sets in the white and silver NXEC corporate livery within two years. However, the collapse of NXEC in 2009 and its replacement with East Coast saw this repainting programme cancelled. As a result, 91111 was the only locomotive to receive the full National Express livery.<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/emdjt42/5097274026/in/photostream/ 91111 East Coast Newcastle Central.] Flickr. Retrieved 5 November 2010</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, a new silver livery with a purple stripe was unveiled by East Coast.<ref>{{cite journal |page=3 |journal=Railway Herald |issue=223 |url=http://archive.railwayherald.com/Issue233.pdf |date=9 August 2010 |editor-first=Richard |editor-last=Tuplin |issn=1751-8091 |title=East Coast goes silver and purple! |first=Ron |last=Cover |accessdate=12 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715151659/http://archive.railwayherald.com/Issue233.pdf |archivedate=15 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> By February 2011, locomotives 91101,<ref>{{cite web |title= 91101 at Leeds |url= http://www.traintesting.com/images/91101%20EC%20livery%20Leeds.jpg |date= 5 October 2010 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110927103135/http://www.traintesting.com/images/91101%20EC%20livery%20Leeds.jpg |archivedate= 27 September 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> 91106, 91107 and 91109 carried this livery. Locomotive 91101 was soon given maroon vinyls, with Flying Scotsman branding. Locomotive 91107 was given promotional [[Skyfall (film)|\"Skyfall\"]] vinyls for a time during 2012/3. The locomotive later returned to conventional [[Virgin Trains East Coast]] livery. Locomotive 91110 carries 'BBMF' Battle Of Britain Memorial Flight livery. By 2013, all locomotives carried the standard East Coast livery of silver/grey with a purple stripe. 91118 was the last locomotive to carry GNER/NXEC livery. All Mark 4 coaches and DVTs have since been repainted. On 14 October 2014 at [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle station]], locomotive 91111 was unveiled in a commemorative [[World War One]] livery and named 'For The Fallen'.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.mediacentre.eastcoast.co.uk/News/EAST-COAST-UNVEILS-MOVING-TRIBUTE-FOR-THE-FALLEN-48d.aspx |title=East Coast unveils tribute \"For the Fallen\" |publisher=East Coast |date=14 October 2014 |accessdate=5 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219213121/http://www.mediacentre.eastcoast.co.uk/News/EAST-COAST-UNVEILS-MOVING-TRIBUTE-FOR-THE-FALLEN-48d.aspx |archivedate=19 December 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Class 91 fleet has carried [[nameplate]]s applied in various batches and themes. Immediately after repainting into GNER colours in the late 1990s, all locomotives were briefly nameless. Having initially been applied to only a few locomotives in the early 1990s using cast-iron plates, eventually the whole fleet was named, many multiple times, until all were removed in 2008. In 2011, in response to customer requests, East Coast resumed the practice. It began by naming No. 91109 as ''[[Sir Bobby Robson]]'' with cast-iron plates, unveiled in a ceremony at [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle station]] on 29 March by his widow Elsie and [[Alan Shearer]].<ref name=BBC29Mar2011Train>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-12890755\n|title=Sir Bobby Robson name given to train\n|work=BBC News\n|date=29 March 2011\n|accessdate=29 March 2011\n}}</ref><ref name=EastCoastTrains29Mar2011>{{cite press release \n |url=http://www.eastcoast.co.uk/about-us/Press-Release/2011/EAST-COAST-NAMES-TRAIN-SIR-BOBBY-ROBSON/ \n |title=East Coast Names Train Sir Bobby Robson \n |publisher=East Coast \n |date=29 March 2011 \n |accessdate=29 March 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5xXxVrMou?url=http://www.eastcoast.co.uk/about-us/Press-Release/2011/EAST-COAST-NAMES-TRAIN-SIR-BOBBY-ROBSON/ \n |archivedate=29 March 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n }}</ref>\n\nLocomotive 91023 was involved in both the [[Hatfield rail crash]] and the [[Great Heck rail crash]]. After refurbishment in 2001, it was renumbered 91132 (rather than 91123).\n\nIn November 2012, unit 91114 had a second pantograph added as a pilot project operated jointly by Eversholt Rail Group, East Coast, ESG, Wabtec Rail and [[Brecknell Willis]]. The new design uses the same mounting positions as a conventional pantograph but pairs two pantograph arms in an opposing configuration. If there is an ADD (Automatic Dropping Device) activation or the pantograph becomes detached, the train can keep going, so the system provides redundancy in the event of a pantograph/OLE failure.<ref>{{cite news |title=Second pantograph fitted to '91' in bid to cut failures |page=6 |work=Rail |location= Peterborough |date=28 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.railwaystrategies.co.uk/article-page.php?contentid=16934&issueid=475| title = Duplex pantograph prototype unveiled|date = 1 February 2013\n|work = www.railwaystrategies.co.uk|accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>This has since been removed, but the extended lower roof is still visible.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Class\n!Operator\n!No. of locos\n!Locomotive Numbers\n!Status\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |'''Class 91/1'''\n|London North Eastern Railway\n|19\n|91101-91102 91105-91107, 91109-91111, 91114-91116, 91118-91119, 91121, 91124-91127, 91130\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Originally numbered 91001-91031.\n|-\n|Europhoenix\n|2\n|91117, 91120\n|-\n|Off Lease/Storage\n|10\n|91103, 91104, 91108, 91112, 91113, 91122, 91128, 91129 \n91131 \n\n91132\n|}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Table of withdrawals\n! Year !! Quantity in<br>service at<br>start of year !! Quantity<br>withdrawn !! Numbers\n|-\n| 2019 || 31 || 6 || align=left | 91103/104/108/117/120/122\n|-\n| 2020 || 25 || 6 || align=\"left\" | 91112/113/128/129/131/132\n|}\n\n==Operators==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Operator\n! Years\n! Livery\n! Image\n|-\n|[[InterCity (British Rail)|InterCity]]\n| 1988\u20141996\n| Intercity Swallow\n|[[File:Peterborough Station, 1992 geograph-3967343-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|200px|91021 at Peterborough in 1992.]]\n|-\n|[[GNER|Great North Eastern Railway]]\n| 1996\u20142007\n| Navy blue with red detailing\n|[[File:Hugh_llewelyn_91_101_(6749175251).jpg|200px|91101 \"City of London\" at King's Cross in July 2007.]]\n|-\n|[[National Express East Coast]]\n| 2007\u20142009\n| National Express corporate grey\n|[[File:Hugh llewelyn 91 111 (5624186675).jpg|200px|91111 at Kings Cross in March 2009.]]\n|-\n|[[East Coast (train operating company)|East Coast]]\n| 2009\u20142015\n| East Coast silver with purple stripe\n|[[File:91 106 Kings Cross(8077572452).jpg|200px|91106 at King's Cross in August 2012.]]\n|-\n|[[Virgin Trains East Coast]]\n| 2015\u20142018\n| Virgin Trains corporate red and white\n|[[File:York - VTEC 91124 leaving for London.JPG|200px|91124 at York in April 2015.]]\n|-\n|[[London North Eastern Railway]]\n| 2018\u2014\n| LNER red and white (VTEC red/white with LNER branding)\n|[[File:Kings Cross - LNER 91125 ecs.JPG|200px|91125 at King's Cross in July 2018.]]\n|-\n|[[Europhoenix]]\n| 2019\u2014\n| Europhoenix grey, silver and red (with a phoenix motif branding)\n|[[File:Leicester TMD - Europhoenix 91117.JPG|200px|91117 at Leicester TMD in October 2019.]]\n|}\n\n===Current Operations===\nThe fleet, which was previously operated by [[InterCity (British Rail)|InterCity]] and then [[Great North Eastern Railway|GNER]], [[National Express East Coast]], [[East Coast (train operating company)|East Coast]] and [[Virgin Trains East Coast]], is currently run by [[London North Eastern Railway]]. Since [[Privatisation of British Rail|privatisation]], the fleet has been owned by [[Eversholt Rail Group]] who lease it to the operators. Between 2000 and 2003, the whole fleet underwent a refit (Project Delta) to improve reliability. The Class 91 units were refurbished at [[Bombardier Transportation]] at its [[Doncaster Works]]. This has resulted in the renumbering of the fleet from 910xx to 911xx.  During this time, GNER hired in [[British Rail Class 90|Class 90]] locomotives to provide cover.<ref>\n{{cite book\n  | last = Pritchard, Fox & Hall\n  | title = British Railways Locomotives & Coaching Stock 2007\n  | publisher = Platform 5 Publishing Ltd.\n  | year = 2007\n  | location = Sheffield, UK\n  | isbn = 978-1-902336-55-8\n}}</ref>\n\n===Future Operations===\n\n[[Europhoenix]] purchased 91117 and 91120 in September 2019. They were repainted at [[Bounds Green TMD]] before moving to [[UK Rail Leasing]]'s [[Leicester]] depot. They are to be re-geared for freight operation in Europe.<ref>[https://www.railmagazine.com/news/network/europhoenix-earmarks-91s-for-european-freight-use Europhoenix earmarks \u201891s\u2019 for European freight use] ''Rail'' 10 October 2019</ref>\n\n[[Rail Operations Group]] have expressed interest in using the Class 91s on high speed logistics trains.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Clinnick |first1=Richard |title=May start for withdrawal of LNER's redundant trains |magazine=Rail Magazine |date=24 April 2019 |issue=877 |page=32 |publisher=Bauer Media |location=Peterborough |issn=0953-4563}}</ref>\n\n[[Virgin Trains West Coast]] have also proposed to use Class 91s and Mark 4 carriages for an hourly open-access service from [[Euston railway station|London Euston]] to [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool Lime Street]], which would be shorter than the current nine-car sets to enable quicker acceleration.<ref> Clinnick, Richard. [https://www.railmagazine.com/news/network/virgin-proposes-london-liverpool-open-access-service \"Virgin proposes London-Liverpool open access service\"], ''[[Rail (magazine)]]'', Peterborough, 11 June 2019. Retrieved on 11 June 2019.</ref>\n\n[[Grand Union (train operating company)|Grand Union]] is proposing to operate InterCity 225s on [[Paddington railway station|London Paddington]] to [[Cardiff Central railway station|Cardiff Central]] and [[Euston railway station|London Euston]] to [[Stirling railway station (Scotland)|Stirling]] services.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20190622221304/https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/cardiff-london-open-access-plan.html Cardiff - London open access plan] ''[[Railway Gazette International]]'' 19 June 2019</ref><ref>[https://orr.gov.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/41688/grand-union-trains-notification-form.pdf - Notification to the Office of Rail and Road of a Proposed service that may be subject to the economic equilibrium] Office of Rail and Road</ref>\n\n== Preservation ==\nUpon retirement, 91110 will be preserved as part of the [[National Collection]], having been nominated by the [[Railway Heritage Committee]].<ref>Class 60 to be saved for preservation ''Rail'' issue 678 7 September 2011 page 33</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Literature===\n*{{citation|author = P.J. Donnison| author2= G.R. West| title = The design and development of the class 91 locomotive| journal = IEE Conference Publication| number = 312| pages =294\u2013298| editor = Institution of Electrical Engineers| date = 25\u201328 September 1989| url =https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/51890|isbn = 978-0-85296-384-5}}\n*{{citation|author = P.C. Bennett| title = Aspects of the design, construction and testing of BRB's Class 90 and 91 locomotive transformers| journal = IEE Conference Publication| number = 312| pages =279\u2013283| editor = Institution of Electrical Engineers| date = 25\u201328 September 1989| url =https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/51887|isbn = 978-0-85296-384-5}}\n*{{citation| url =https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/307959| title= The Class 91 locomotive. Learning from the APT|author = R. Dettmer| journal = IEE Review| date =  12 May 1998| volume =34| issue = 5| pages = 188\u2013189| issn=0953-5683| doi= 10.1049/ir:19880072}}\n*{{Cite journal | last1 = Broom | first1 = M. L. | last2 = Smart | first2 = G. W. | doi = 10.1243/PIME_PROC_1990_204_200_02 | title = The design, manufacture and assembly of the wheelset for the British Rail Class 91, 25 kV, 225 km/h locomotive | journal = Proceedings of the Institution of Mechanical Engineers, Part F: Journal of Rail and Rapid Transit | volume = 204 | issue = 26 | pages = 141 | year = 1990 | pmid =  | pmc = }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|British Rail Class 91}}\n* {{citati